🔷 🔥 What is a Query Param?

👉 It is data passed in URL after ?

http://localhost:8080/books?keyword=java

👉 Here:

keyword = java
🔷 🔥 How to Read Query Param in Spring

👉 Use @RequestParam

✅ Example (Your Book App)
@GetMapping("/books")
public String getBooks(@RequestParam(required = false) String keyword,
                       Model model) {

    List<Book> books = service.searchBooks(keyword);

    model.addAttribute("books", books);
    model.addAttribute("keyword", keyword);

    return "books";
}
🔷 🔥 What @RequestParam Does

👉 It takes value from URL:

/books?keyword=java

👉 And assigns:

keyword = "java"
🔷 🔥 Required vs Optional
Required (default)
@RequestParam String keyword

❌ Error if missing

Optional ✅
@RequestParam(required = false) String keyword

✔ Works even if no param

🔷 🔥 Default Value
@RequestParam(defaultValue = "") String keyword
🔷 🔥 Multiple Query Params
/books?name=java&price=100
@GetMapping("/books")
public String getBooks(@RequestParam String name,
                       @RequestParam int price) {
}
🔷 🔥 HTML Form (GET method)
<form method="get" action="/books">
    <input type="text" name="keyword" placeholder="Search"/>
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>
What is this?

👉 This automatically sends query param

🔷 🔥 Flow
HTML Form → URL (?keyword=java) → @RequestParam → Controller
🔥 Real Example
URL	Output
/books	all books
